edge, some areas have remained stubbornly underdeveloped and a full or comprehensive consideration of the philosophical issues of tourism represents one such significant knowledge gap. A key aim of this book therefore is to provide an initial mapping of, and fresh insights into this territory. In doing so it discusses key philosophical questions in the field such as What is tourism? Who is a tourist? What is wisdom? What is it to know something? What is the nature of reality? Why are some destinations considered beautiful? Why is tourism desirable? What is good and bad tourism? What are desirable ends? These and similar topics are addressed this book under the headings of truth, beauty and virtue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTourismxPhilosophy. 4aPHILOSOPHY. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  abeauty of tourism.  aethical tourism.  aethics and tourism.  aphilosophy of tourism.  apost-disciplinary tourism.  atourism aesthetics.  atourism and philosophy.  atourism development.  atourism knowledge.  atruth, beauty and virtue.1 aAteljevic, Irena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyikoru, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButcher, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColes, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuval, David Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFennell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, C. Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannam, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJamal, Tazim, econtributor.4ctb4h